I'm not quite that old, so my perspective is mostly limited to the development of the modern consumer internet. I mean, I even got some HTML classes in high school. Everyone on the internet could, and would, make their own websites. That general level of base expertise has plummeted, and been taken over by the service industry.

I'm only in my late twenties, but I have some perspective; the whole point is that we've always lived under the phenomenon. You, me, everyone here, etc., we're all byproducts of the internet because its commercialization in the early-ninties made it accessible and user-friendly to everyone. The old guard of the internet would've been the generation of late-seventies/early-eighties kids who were savvy enough to access it back then by whatever means they could devise on their own or circumstantially obtain, and web browsers like AOL took that and several protocols that were relatively exclusive at the time, and baked it all into one software solution that anyone and their grandmother could use at the time. Naturally, as people started using more than IM and email, they were going to begin trickling into spaces and communities that were once only accessible to a handful of internet users. In a sense, chan culture has more or less inherited and always exhibited that hysteria over new users pouring in and diluting the subculture most of us have grown up within for the past fifteen years. If you consider yourself an oldfag (to wit, you've been here all summer since at least '07/'08), you've got the truest contemporary perspective on it around.
